<PubmedArticle><MedlineCitation Status="MEDLINE" Owner="NLM" IndexingMethod="Automated"><PMID Version="1">41314608</PMID><DateCompleted><Year>2026</Year><Month>03</Month><Day>23</Day></DateCompleted><DateRevised><Year>2026</Year><Month>03</Month><Day>23</Day></DateRevised><Article PubModel="Print-Electronic"><Journal><ISSN IssnType="Electronic">2405-4577</ISSN><JournalIssue CitedMedium="Internet"><Volume>72</Volume><PubDate><Year>2026</Year><Month>Apr</Month></PubDate></JournalIssue><Title>Clinical nutrition ESPEN</Title><ISOAbbreviation>Clin Nutr ESPEN</ISOAbbreviation></Journal><ArticleTitle>Sodium intake, serum sodium levels and impact on overhydration of patients on hemodialysis.</ArticleTitle><Pagination><StartPage>102820</StartPage><MedlinePgn>102820</MedlinePgn></Pagination><ELocationID EIdType="doi" ValidYN="Y">10.1016/j.clnesp.2025.11.135</ELocationID><ELocationID EIdType="pii" ValidYN="Y">S2405-4577(25)03128-6</ELocationID><Abstract><AbstractText Label="OBJECTIVE" NlmCategory="OBJECTIVE">Evaluate the relationship between dietary intake, dietary and serum sodium, Interdialytic weight gain (IDWG), and overhydration in hemodialysis (HD) patients.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="METHODS" NlmCategory="METHODS">This observational, longitudinal study includes 582 patients from 37 Portuguese HD centers. Correlations between sodium intake, serum sodium, hyperhydration, dietary intake, and IDWG were analyzed using Spearman's coefficient. Mann-Whitney U test analyzed associations of dietary and serum sodium and IDWG with relative overhydration (&#x2265;15 % or &lt;15 %). Logistic regression assessed the impact of serum sodium and dietary intake on hyperhydration. Cox regression assessed the association of hyperhydration with mortality risk at 24 months. Multiple linear regression explored relationships between GPI, sodium intake, and blood pressure. Significance level adopted: p &lt; 0.05.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="RESULTS" NlmCategory="RESULTS">Sodium intake correlates with blood pressure. People with hyperhydration have higher IDWG. Some foods showed correlations with dietary and serum sodium, IDWG and relative overhydration. Consumption of bacon, savory snacks, carrots, bell peppers, cherries, and soup predicted greater hyperhydration, while rice, cookies, and grapes show the opposite effect, regardless of age, sex, diabetes, and HD duration.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="CONCLUSION" NlmCategory="CONCLUSIONS">IDWG is associated with hyperhydration, and sodium intake correlates positively with blood pressure. Certain foods influence serum sodium, IDWG, and the risk of hyperhydration, highlighting the need for personalized dietary strategies to optimize hydration management in HD patients.</AbstractText><CopyrightInformation>Copyright &#xa9; 2025 The Author(s). Published by Elsevier Ltd.. All rights reserved.</CopyrightInformation></Abstract><AuthorList CompleteYN="Y"><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Anjo Dias</LastName><ForeName>Carolina</ForeName><Initials>C</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>University of Lisbon Faculty of Medicine, Portugal. Electronic address: carolina.dianjo@gmail.com.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Guerreiro</LastName><ForeName>Catarina Sousa</ForeName><Initials>CS</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Nutrition Laboratory, Faculty of Medicine, Academic Center of Medicine of Lisbon, University of Lisbon, 1649-028 Lisbon, Portugal; Institute of Environmental Health, Faculty of Medicine, University of Lisbon, 1649-028 Lisbon, Portugal.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Garagarza</LastName><ForeName>Cristina</ForeName><Initials>C</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Nutrition Laboratory, Faculty of Medicine, Academic Center of Medicine of Lisbon, University of Lisbon, 1649-028 Lisbon, Portugal; Nutrition Department, Nephrocare, 1750 Lisbon, Portugal.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author></AuthorList><Langu